Project Goals

How humans acquire new languages, and why some people are better at it than others, remains a remarkably mysterious question. While it is well-known that children are the most efficient language learners and that language-learning ability declines with age, the specific factors contributing to different language learning outcomes in adulthood are more complicated. Here, we plan on using a large dataset of close to 650,000 individuals to disentangle some of these factors. In particular, we are curious to see whether there are any patterns in performance on test questions among adult English learners across various linguistic groups. In addition, we aim to determine whether adult native speakers to languages more grammatically different from English perform systematically worse than speakers of grammatically similar languages. While the original study associated with this dataset (Hartshorne et al, 2018) examined differences in learning curves for speakers of languages of different official genuses, we will group languages based only on grammatical similarity.

Supplementary information

A critical period for second language acquisition: Evidence from 2/3 million English speakers

Affecting factors in second language learning

A Review of the Role of Cross-Language Similarity in L2 (Morpho)Syntactic Processing as Revealed by fMRI and ERP Methods

Speakers dataset

ETL

We came across this dataset in the "Data Is Plural" archive and downloaded it from OSF. We considered several similar datasets for this project, but this one stood out due to the large number of variables and observations, as well as its being associated with a study whose conclusions we could build on. The original dataset included the following variables:

id Unique subject ID

date Date at start of experiment

time Time at start of experiment

gender

age

natlangs List of subject's native languages

primelangs List of subject's primary language now

dyslexia Did subject report difficulty with reading?

psychiatric Did subject report any psychiatric disorders

education highest level of education

Eng_start age at start of English learning

Eng_country_yrs number of years living in English-speaking country

house_Eng subject lives with any native English speakers?

dictionary subject reported using a dictionary to complete experiment

already_participated Subject reported prior participation in experiment

countries countries lived in

currcountry country currently lived in

US_region regions of USA lived in

UK_region regions of UK lived in

Can_region regions of Canada lived in

Ebonics speaker of Ebonics?

Ir_region county of Ireland lived in

UK_constituency constituency of UK lived in

nat_Eng native speaker of English

lived_Eng_per Percentage of years speaking English that lived in English-speaking country.

Eng_little values are monoeng (native speaker of English only), bileng (native speaker of English + at least one other lang), lot (immersion learner), little (non-immersion learner).

q1, q2, etc. test questions, with subparts

correct percentage of critical items correct

elogit elogit of correct (not sure what this means)

In the following section, we remove variables likely of little relevance, create new columns to more easily access information separated by commas in individual cells, make values within columns consistent and of the correct data type, and lastly, tidy it up.

def replace_school_with_NAN(entry, allowed_list):
    if entry not in allowed_list:
        return np.nan
    return entry

                'Some Undergrad (higher ed)', 'High School Degree (12-13 years)',

Filtering for our sample: Since the original study defined the critical age for second language acquisition as roughly 17, we filtered the dataframe for learners who started learning English after 17, and in addition, did not learn English through an immersion program and did not currently speak English as a primary language. We expect that this sample will make more errors (allowing us to avoid ceiling effects) and that the grammatical errors they make will be more biased towards the grammar of their native language.

In[8]:

Features dataset

We also parsed the following dataset from the World Atlas of Language Structures Online (WALS) webpage, which has a number of datasets on structural features of various languages. The questions in the English proficiency test from the first dataset were not explicitly testing specific elements of syntactic knowledge, so we selected 35 grammatical features that seemed relevant to the test questions.

Using these features, we hoped to create rough groupings of languages based on structural similarity rather than geographic similarity and assess each grouping's performance on the test questions.

import glob

# Glob all csv files:
all_csvs = glob.glob('*.csv')

# Create base df for later merging:
df_features = pd.read_csv('genitive_noun.csv',sep='\t').drop(columns = ['description','value'])

# Iterate through list and merge dfs:
for file in all_csvs:
  # Print file name for debugging
  print(f"Processing file: {file}")

  # Read in current file and slice for non-redundant columns:
  df_current = pd.read_csv(file, sep='\t', on_bad_lines='skip')
  current_name = file[:-4] # Get name of file for df columns

  # Rename value and description columns
  df_current = df_current.rename(
      columns={
          "value": current_name + "_value",
          "description": current_name + "_description",
      }
  )

  # Select only the columns to merge
  df_current_sliced = df_current[['name', current_name + '_value', current_name + '_description']]

  # Perform the merge
  df_features = df_features.merge(df_current_sliced, on='name', how='outer')

# Drop unnecessary variables
df_features = df_features.drop(columns=['wals code', 'latitude', 'longitude', 'area'], errors='ignore') #ignore if column doesn't exist

from sklearn.metrics import pairwise_distances
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.impute import KNNImputer

# For visualization, filter by the top 30 most common languages in the dataset
df_lang_30_index = df_lang_sample['natlang'].value_counts()[:30].index
df_features = df_features[df_features['natlang'].isin(df_lang_30_index)]

# Dummify feature variables
df_features_desc = df_features.filter(regex='_description$')
df_features_encode = pd.get_dummies(df_features_desc)

# Apply KNN imputation
imputer = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=5)
df_features_imputed = imputer.fit_transform(df_features_encode)

# Convert imputed array back to DataFrame
df_features_desc = pd.DataFrame(df_features_imputed, columns=df_features_encode.columns, index=df_features_desc.index)

# Standardize data
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(df_features_encode)
df_features_sc = scaler.transform(df_features_encode)

# Create the distance matrix
D = pairwise_distances(df_features_encode, metric='euclidean')
np.fill_diagonal(D, np.nan)
df_features_sc = pd.DataFrame(D, index=df_features['natlang'], columns=df_features['natlang'])
display(df_features_sc)

There is a moderately strong relationship between syntactic similarity to English and overall test performance, which is surprising since we aren't controlling for any other variables.

While there are clearly some languages that are more similar than others, as visible on the distance matrix, we decided to use K means clustering to be more certain of the groups of languages. We experimented with several different numbers of clusters, but decided on 4.

In[27]:

df_eng_dist_concat.sort_values(by='cluster')

Overall, the groups visible on the PCA plot are similar to the groups given previously by the K means clustering algorithm. To statistically test for significant differences in the overall performance of the clusters, we performed a one-way ANOVA and a post-hoc Tukey's test. The only group differences that we failed to reject were between cluster 0 and clusters 2 and 3.

This table shows that there are not significant differences in the performance on each of the 95 test questions. This isn't great news for the model that we will build in the next section, but we will still try it out. While we could restrict our model to just the questions that the clusters answer most differently, this could artificially improve the model -- it may just be that the four clusters do not perform differently systematically.

Modeling

In the final section of this project, we create a k-nearest neighbors classifier to predict a given participant's language cluster based on their answers to the test questions.

In[35]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

df_model = pd.concat([df_lang_sample[['cluster','natlang']],df_lang_sample[question_cols]],axis=1)

df_model = df_model.dropna()

# Split data into training and validation sets
x_train = df_model.drop(columns=['cluster','natlang']).sample(frac=.5, random_state=1)
y_train = df_model['cluster'].sample(frac=.5, random_state=1).dropna()

x_test = df_model.drop(columns=['cluster','natlang']).drop(x_train.index)
y_test = df_model['cluster'].drop(x_train.index)

# Standardize the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(x_train)
x_train_sc = scaler.transform(x_train)
x_test_sc = scaler.transform(x_test)

def knnclass(k):
  # Fit the k-nearest neighbors model
  model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
  model.fit(x_train_sc, y_train)

  #predict the training data
  y_train_pred = model.predict(x_train_sc)

  #predict the validation data
  y_test_pred = model.predict(x_test_sc)

  confusion_mat = pd.crosstab(y_test, y_test_pred)
  confusion_mat = confusion_mat.reindex(columns=range(0,4)) #ensures that the confusion matrix has the correct dimensions
  confusion_mat = confusion_mat.fillna(0) # replace NaNs from line above

  accuracy = np.diag(confusion_mat).sum() / confusion_mat.to_numpy().sum()

  return accuracy

# Test the model for varying values of k
ks = range(1,100)
accuracies = [knnclass(k) for k in ks]

In[40]:
# Measuring the success of the model

true_pos = np.diag(confusion_mat).sum()
false_pos = (confusion_mat.sum(axis=0) - np.diag(confusion_mat))
false_neg = (confusion_mat.sum(axis=1) - np.diag(confusion_mat))

# Assess the precision, recall, and f-score of the model
precision = true_pos / (true_pos + false_pos)
recall = true_pos / (true_pos + false_neg)
f_score = precision * recall / (precision + recall)

precision = precision.rename('Precision').rename_axis(index=None)
recall = recall.rename('Recall').rename_axis(index=None)
f_score = f_score.rename('F-Score').rename_axis(index=None)

pd.concat([precision,recall,f_score],axis=1).rename_axis(index='Cluster')

The confusion matrix shows that the model is disproportionately predicting Cluster 1. Accordingly, the F1 scores -- which summarize of the overall predictive performance of the model -- are not optimal, the highest not even being 0.5. Given that we did not find significant differences in the results for each test question, this is expected.

It may be that grouping into just 4 clusters obscured some real differences between individual languages. In a future analysis, a classifier could be used to predict native language from test answers.

Conclusion

In this project, we built on the findings of Hartshorne et al., 2018 by examining whether (1) speakers of native languages more grammatically different from English who began learning English after the critical critical period performed worse on a test of English proficiency and (2) whether grammatically similar language groups performed differently from each other. To test the second claim and the validity of these groupings, we built a classifier that predicts language group from test answers. While the model's ability to do so was limited, our analysis nonetheless demonstrates that there is a relatively strong negative correlation between overall test performance and grammatical distance from English, which supports the first hypothesis. Some languages being harder to learn than others (particularly as adults) is often explained in terms of phonological differences between languages; this result shows that syntactic dissimilarities alone may also account for diffifulty in learning new languages among adults.
